MEDS 2024 Applicant Statistics

This script analyzes the diversity of our applicant pool and creates a dataset, diversity_contributions.csv.

Setup

Read in data

  • read_excel() reads in the raw datasheet that Student Affairs downloads from the graduate portal
  • clean_names() from the janitor package to make the column names nice and readable
  • mutate() creates a new column, application_id_name. The values in this column are a combination of the values from application_id, first_name and last_name. These are combined using the paste0() function.
raw <-  read_excel(here("data/Application Export 231204.xlsx")) %>% #read in excel sheet
  clean_names() %>% #this turns the column names into clean, readable names
  filter(objective1 == "MDS") %>% 
  mutate(application_id_name = 
           paste0(last_name, ", ", first_name, ": ", application_id)) %>%
  mutate(dob = gsub(' UTC','',dob))

Diversity dataset

We can obtain information from the application about an applicants gender identity, racial background, if they have military service, if they are first generation, and whether or not they are citizens of a developing country.

Identify Under-represented minorities

Create an object called urms which contains the three under-represented minorities (URM) that fall within the reported IPEDS Category section of the application. By saving this in an object we can easily assess whether or not an applicant has a URM category in their application.

urms <- c("African American / Black", "American Indian / Alaska Native")

Assess diversity contributions

Using the raw dataset we create 6 new columns based on a set of conditions. Each of these columns will have either a Y (yes) or N (no) based on whether they meet the conditions. The only exception is for woman_nonbinary where a U will be used if the applicant did not disclose their gender.

woman_nonbinary

Y if an applicant lists F
N if applicant lists M
U if applicant lists U

urm (under-represented group)

Y if hispanic_latino is TRUE and the applicant is a citizen of the US or Permanent Resident
Y if the applicant lists one of the three urms in the racial_categories column and the applicant is a citizen of the US or Permanent Resident
N if neither of these are true

international

Y if visa is F-1 Student, J-1 Student or other unique entry indicating international status

undocumented

Y if visa is undocumented status or other unique entry indicating undocumented, otherwise N

military

Y if any of Discharged Veteran, National Guard, or Active Duty are in military_service, otherwise N

first_gen

Y if first_generation is Y, otherwise N

We then select these 5 diversity columns along with the application_id_name along with some additional columns for our summary statistics.

The report_to_ipeds column is based on the conditions listed on the IPEDS website.

diversity_df <- raw %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(woman_nonbinary = case_when(
    gender == "Female" ~ "Yes",
    gender == "Male" ~ "No",
    gender == "Unknown" ~ "Undisclosed"),
    urm = case_when(
      hispanic_latino == TRUE & citizenship_country == "United States" ~ "Yes", #US citizens that are hispanic/latino
      hispanic_latino == TRUE & visa == "Permanent Resident" ~ "Yes", #permanent residents that are hispanic/latino
      TRUE %in% str_detect(racial_categories, urms) == TRUE & citizenship_country == "US" ~ "Yes", #US citizens that identify as an URM
      TRUE %in% str_detect(racial_categories, urms) == TRUE & visa == "Permanent Resident" ~ "Yes", #Permanent residents that identify as an URM
      TRUE ~ "No"
    ),
    international = ifelse(visa %in% c("F-1 Student", "F-2 Student Spouse", "J-1"), "Yes", "No"),
    english_language_skills = case_when(
      toefl_total_score < 95  ~ "Poor",
      ielts_overall < 7 ~ "Poor",
      toefl_total_score >= 95 & toefl_total_score < 100 ~ "Good",
      ielts_overall >=7 & ielts_overall <=7.5 ~ "Good",
      toefl_total_score >99 ~ "Strong",
      ielts_overall >=8 ~ "Strong",
      TRUE ~ ""),
    undocumented = case_when(
      visa == "undocumented status" ~ "Yes", 
      is.na(visa) ~ "No",
      TRUE ~ "No"),
    military = ifelse(military_service %in% c("Discharged Veteran", "National Guard", "Active Duty"), "Yes", "No"),
    first_gen = ifelse(first_generation == "Yes", "Yes", "No"), 
    report_to_ipeds = case_when(
      hispanic_latino == TRUE & international == "No" ~ "Hispanic",
      hispanic_latino == FALSE & !str_detect(racial_categories, ",") & international == "No" ~ racial_categories,
      hispanic_latino == FALSE & str_detect(racial_categories, ",") & international == "No" ~ "Two or more races",
      international == "Yes" ~ "Nonresident alien",
      is.na(hispanic_latino) & is.na(racial_categories) ~ "Unknown race and ethnicity",
      hispanic_latino == FALSE & is.na(racial_categories) ~ "Unknown race and ethnicity",
      is.na(hispanic_latino) & !is.na(racial_categories) & !str_detect(racial_categories, ",") ~ racial_categories,
      is.na(hispanic_latino) & !is.na(racial_categories) & str_detect(racial_categories, ",") ~ "Two or more races"
    )) %>%
  select(application_id_name, woman_nonbinary, urm, first_gen, international, undocumented, military, report_to_ipeds, english_language_skills)

Save diversity dataset

These 6 columns will be included in the google sheet we share with faculty reviewers. We want to save the applicant_id_name and the 5 diversity categories.

diversity_df %>%
  write_csv(here("data/diversity_contributions.csv"))

Summary statistics:

17% are under-represented minorities
62% are women
21% are international
16% are first generation
6% identify as multiracial
0% are undocumented

labels <- c("Female", "Male", "Undisclosed")

ggplot(raw, aes(x = gender)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(y = "Number of students",
       x = "",
       title = "Gender identity") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels= labels) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size=12))

div_df_ggplot <- diversity_df %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 2:9) %>%
  rename(diversity_category = name) %>%
  filter(!diversity_category %in% c("report_to_ipeds", "english_language_skills")) %>%
  filter(value == "Yes") %>%
  group_by(diversity_category) %>%
  summarize(percentage = n()/nrow(diversity_df))

labs <- c("First Generation", "Underrepresented Minority", "International", "Women/Nonbinary" )
ggplot(div_df_ggplot, aes(x = reorder(diversity_category, percentage), y = percentage,  xlab="")) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=.5, position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "", y = "Percentage (%)", fill = "", title = "Diversity Contributions") + 
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format()) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels= labs)

Age

age <- raw %>%
  select(application_id_name, dob) %>%
  mutate(age = trunc(as.numeric(difftime(Sys.Date(), dob, units = "days")) / 365.25))

ggplot(age, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_minimal()

The median age is 24 with a range of 20 to 34

IPEDS Categories

ipeds <- diversity_df %>%
  group_by(report_to_ipeds) %>%
  summarize(percentage = n()/nrow(raw))
  

#plot

ggplot(ipeds, aes(x = reorder(report_to_ipeds, percentage), y = percentage,  xlab="")) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=.5, position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "", y = "Percentage (%)", fill = "", title = "Race & Ethnicity of applicants", subtitle = "These categories align with stated definitions by the Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System (IPEDS)") + 
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format())

Undergraduate degrees

This wordcloud shows all of the different undergraduate majors listed by our applicants. The size of the words increases with the number of occurrences.

degrees <- raw %>% 
  group_by(ug1_major) %>%
  summarize(count = n())

ggplot(degrees, aes(label = ug1_major, size = count, color = ug1_major)) +
  geom_text_wordcloud() +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 6) +
  theme_minimal()

Where are our students coming from?

#united states locations
us_ug_locations <- raw %>%
  select(ug1_location) %>%
  filter(str_detect(ug1_location, "US - ")) %>%
  separate(ug1_location, into = c("country", "state"), sep = " - ") %>%
  group_by(state) %>%
  summarize(count = n())

plot_usmap(data = us_ug_locations, values = "count") + 
  scale_fill_continuous(
    low = "lightblue", high = "darkblue", name = "Number of students", label = scales::comma
  ) + theme(legend.position = "right")

#international locations
int_ug_locations <- raw %>%
  select(ug1_location) %>%
  filter(!str_detect(ug1_location, "US - ")) %>%
  group_by(ug1_location) %>%
  summarize(count = n())

ggplot(int_ug_locations, aes(x = reorder(ug1_location, count), y = count,  xlab="")) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",  position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "", y = "Count", fill = "", title = "International applicants") + 
  coord_flip()

#turn data into sf object
df_sf = st_as_sf(ug_institutions %>% filter(!is.na(school_name)), coords = c("LONGITUDE", "LATITUDE"), 
                 crs = 4326, agr = "constant") %>%
  select(-CITY, -STABBR, -ug1_name)

mapview::mapview(df_sf, legend = FALSE, cex = "count", 
                 zcol = "school_name", popup = popupTable(df_sf, zcol = "count"))
